description: A court opinion that establishes legal precedent and must be followed by lower courts in future similar cases.
A court opinion that does not establish binding precedent but may be cited as persuasive authority.
A correction issued by the court to fix errors in a previously published opinion.
An opinion written by a judge expressing individual views, often concurring or dissenting from the majority.
A decision made by a single judge, typically on procedural matters, without full panel review.
Orders that pertain to procedural or administrative aspects of a case rather than substantive legal rulings.
